However, historically, the greatest challenge is what comes after we have a vaccine — navigating a broad spectrum of sociopolitical and economic barriers to immunization that often result in unequal vaccine access and global health disparities.
This “first-come, first served” model will likely be the case for a COVID-19 vaccine.
The greatest challenge is navigating a broad spectrum of sociopolitical and economic barriers to immunization that often result in unequal vaccine access and global health disparities.
According to the WHO, vaccine hesitancy was one of the top 10 global health threats of 2019.
It will not be enough to have a COVID-19 vaccine if we are unable to get it to people in hard to reach places in a timely manner, where the need is equally (if not more) dire.